sections.name: Email Headers

sections.description:
Analysis of SPF, DKIM, DMARC and Microsoft anti-spam headers.

For Microsoft anti-spam headers, please click on each item for the relevant documentation:
[PCL](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/exchange/antispam-and-antimalware/antispam-protection/antispam-stamps?view=exchserver-2019) - Phishing Confidence Level.
[BCL](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-365/security/office-365-security/bulk-complaint-level-values?view=o365-worldwide) - Bulk Complaint Level.
[SCL](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-365/security/office-365-security/spam-confidence-levels?view=o365-worldwide) - Spam Confidence Level.
`Note`: The default value is 0, but it can be changed when the "Process Microsoft's Email Headers" playbook runs.

sections.description: In case there were URLs in the email with a score of 3 or above which the user clicked for the email investigated in this incident, they will appear in the **Clicked URLs** table. **Total Malicious URLs Clicks** represents the number of clicks in all emails (other emails as well) associated with any of the malicious URLs found in this email. **Malicious URL Viewed** will be **True** if the click was allowed or the user clicked through, in case it was blocked.
sections.name: Malicious Clicked URLs information

sections.description:
Trigger the incident based on a phishing email attachment.

Please fill in:
1. A name of the incident.
2. The email address for which you're making the report (optional).
3. An EML or MSG file representing the phishing email, or containing another EML or MSG file of the phishing email within it.

If the reporter email address is left blank - user engagement will be skipped in the playbook.
